Now I have enough data for a thorough answer. Let me compile all the patterns found:

---

## TigerBeetle's Naming Convention for Multiple Init Functions

TigerBeetle uses a consistent, systematic convention for multiple constructors: **`init` as the primary/canonical constructor**, and **`init_<noun>` or `init_<adjective>` variants** for alternative constructors. The suffix is a snake_case descriptor of what differentiates that variant. There is no use of `initFoo` (camelCase) anywhere — the entire codebase uses `snake_case` for all function names.

---

### Pattern 1: `init` delegates to a more general `init_<x>`

The most common pattern: `init` is the "easy path" that uses defaults, and it delegates to a lower-level variant that exposes the full parameter set.

#### [`ZipfianGenerator`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/zipfian.zig#L83-L101) — two constructors, one with default `theta`

```zig
pub const ZipfianGenerator = struct {
    theta: f64,
    n: u64,
    zetan: f64,

    /// Create a generator from `[0, items)` with `theta` equal to 0.99.
    pub fn init(items: u64) ZipfianGenerator {
        return ZipfianGenerator.init_theta(items, theta_default);
    }

    /// Create a generator from `[0, items)` with given `theta`.
    pub fn init_theta(items: u64, theta: f64) ZipfianGenerator {
        assert(theta > 0.0);
        assert(theta != 1.0);
        return ZipfianGenerator{
            .theta = theta,
            .n = items,
            .zetan = zeta(items, theta),
        };
    }
};
```

The same pattern applies to [`ZipfianShuffled`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/zipfian.zig#L194-L207) in the same file:

```zig
pub const ZipfianShuffled = struct {
    pub fn init(items: u64, prng: *stdx.PRNG) ZipfianShuffled {
        return ZipfianShuffled.init_theta(items, theta_default, prng);
    }

    pub fn init_theta(items: u64, theta: f64, prng: *stdx.PRNG) ZipfianShuffled { ... }
};
```

There is even a test named `"zipfian-ctors"` explicitly checking that both constructors agree.

---

#### [`MessagePool`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/message_pool.zig#L194-L230) — `init` vs `init_capacity`

`init` accepts a high-level `Options` union and computes the capacity internally, then delegates:

```zig
pub const MessagePool = struct {
    pub fn init(
        allocator: mem.Allocator,
        options: Options,
    ) error{OutOfMemory}!MessagePool {
        return MessagePool.init_capacity(allocator, options.messages_max());
    }

    pub fn init_capacity(
        allocator: mem.Allocator,
        messages_max: u32,
    ) error{OutOfMemory}!MessagePool {
        // allocates raw capacity directly
        ...
    }
};
```

`init_capacity` is the "escape hatch" used by test code that doesn't have a full `Options` context but knows exactly how many messages it needs.

---

### Pattern 2: Parallel constructors with no delegation (different transport/implementation)

When the two constructors produce the same type but through fundamentally different mechanisms (not just defaults), both are named peers with no delegation.

#### [`StatsD`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/trace/statsd.zig#L131-L181) — UDP vs log output

```zig
pub const StatsD = struct {
    implementation: union(enum) {
        udp: struct { socket: std.posix.socket_t, io: *IO, ... },
        log,
    },
    ...

    /// Creates a statsd instance, which will send UDP packets via the IO instance provided.
    pub fn init_udp(
        allocator: std.mem.Allocator,
        process_id: ProcessID,
        io: *IO,
        address: std.net.Address,
    ) !StatsD { ... }

    // Creates a statsd instance, which will log out the packets that would have been sent.
    // Useful so that all of the other code can run and be tested in the simulator.
    pub fn init_log(
        allocator: std.mem.Allocator,
        process_id: ProcessID,
    ) !StatsD { ... }
};
```

Note: no bare `init` at all here — both constructors are explicitly named, and the call site picks from them by name:

```zig
// in src/trace.zig:
.log => StatsD.init_log(allocator, process_id),
.udp => |statsd_options| StatsD.init_udp(allocator, ...),
```

---

### Pattern 3: `init` is the real constructor; `init_<x>` is a convenience for tests

#### [`FreeSet`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/free_set.zig#L115-L165) — `init` vs `init_empty`

```zig
pub const FreeSet = struct {
    pub fn init(allocator: mem.Allocator, options: struct {
        grid_size_limit: usize,
        blocks_released_prior_checkpoint_durability_max: usize,
    }) !FreeSet { ... }

    // A shortcut to initialize an empty free set for tests.
    pub fn init_empty(allocator: mem.Allocator, blocks_count: usize) !FreeSet {
        comptime assert(constants.verify);  // <-- only available in verify/test builds
        var set = try init(allocator, .{
            .grid_size_limit = blocks_count * constants.block_size,
            ...
        });
        return set;
    }
};
```

The `comptime assert(constants.verify)` is TigerBeetle's way of enforcing the variant is test-only.

---

### Pattern 4: `from_<noun>` for constructors that *parse* or *convert* from a different representation

When the constructor deserializes/converts from a raw form rather than initializing fresh, TigerBeetle uses `from_<noun>`:

#### [`MultiversionHeader.init_from_bytes`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/multiversion.zig#L494-L499)

```zig
pub const MultiversionHeader = extern struct {
    /// Parses an instance from a slice of bytes and validates its checksum. Returns a copy.
    pub fn init_from_bytes(bytes: *const [@sizeOf(MultiversionHeader)]u8) !MultiversionHeader {
        const self = std.mem.bytesAsValue(MultiversionHeader, bytes).*;
        try self.verify();
        return self;
    }
};
```

This uses the hybrid `init_from_<noun>` — it's still an init (returns a value), but the noun clarifies the source.

#### [`PRNG.from_seed` and `PRNG.from_seed_testing`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/prng.zig#L110-L123)

`PRNG` itself is a plain struct (no heap), so TigerBeetle uses `from_<noun>` naming (no `init` prefix) since it's a pure conversion:

```zig
pub fn from_seed(seed: u64) PRNG {
    var s = seed;
    return .{ .s = .{
        split_mix_64(&s),
        split_mix_64(&s),
        split_mix_64(&s),
        split_mix_64(&s),
    } };
}

pub fn from_seed_testing() PRNG {
    comptime assert(@import("builtin").is_test);
    return .from_seed(std.testing.random_seed);
}
```

---

### Pattern 5: `RingBuffer` — comptime dispatch, private variant names

In [`RingBufferType`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/ring_buffer.zig#L35-L52), two variants exist for array-backed vs slice-backed buffers. Because the right constructor is selected at comptime, the variants are private and `pub const init` is assigned to the correct one:

```zig
pub const init = switch (buffer_type) {
    .array => init_array,
    .slice => init_slice,
};

fn init_array() RingBuffer {
    comptime assert(buffer_type == .array);
    return .{ .buffer = undefined };
}

fn init_slice(allocator: mem.Allocator, capacity: usize) !RingBuffer {
    comptime assert(buffer_type == .slice);
    ...
}
```

Here `init_array` and `init_slice` are private implementation details; callers just use `init`.

---

### Summary of Conventions

| Scenario | Naming |
|---|---|
| Default params → full params | `init` delegates to `init_<param_name>` |
| Distinct implementations (no default) | Named peers: `init_udp`, `init_log` (no bare `init`) |
| Test/debug shortcut of the real `init` | `init_empty`, `init_capacity`, `from_seed_testing` |
| Parse/convert from bytes/seed/etc. | `init_from_bytes`, or bare `from_seed` (no `init` prefix) |
| Comptime-selected variant | Private `init_array`/`init_slice`, public `init` aliased at comptime |

**The universal rule:** all names are `snake_case`. The suffix after `init_` is a noun or adjective describing *what is different* about that constructor — the source data (`from_bytes`, `from_seed`), a key parameter name (`init_theta`, `init_capacity`), the transport (`init_udp`, `init_log`), or a state adjective (`init_empty`).
